emmo:InverseSquarePlanckMass a owl:NamedIndividual,
        emmo:EMMO_15344998_4490_4b40_b242_c3d92e5cdc27,
        emmo:EMMO_6aa04359_50d6_43d7_b3a7_296bd391bf7d,
        emmo:EMMO_868ae137_4d25_493e_b270_21ea3d94849e,
        emmo:EMMO_b081b346_7279_46ef_9a3d_2c088fcd79f4 ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy <https://w3id.org/emmo/disciplines/units/otherunits-abox#>,
        "http://qudt.org/2.1/vocab/unit"^^xsd:string ;
    skos:altLabel "Inverse Square Planck Mass"@en ;
    skos:prefLabel "InverseSquarePlanckMass"@en ;
    emmo:EMMO_8189b42e_0995_423a_a26c_51168b27c3cf 2.111089e+15 ;
    emmo:EMMO_d088a3cb_d3e3_4eb2_9897_00aef0cb00cd 0e+00 ;
    emmo:elucidation """In physics, the Planck mass, denoted by m_P, is the unit of mass in the system of natural units known as Planck units. It is defined so that ≈  1.2209 × 10 GeV/c₀ = 2.17651(13) × 10 kg, (or 21.7651 μ g), where c₀ is the speed of light in a vacuum, G is the gravitational constant, and ℏ is the reduced Planck constant. Particle physicists and cosmologists often use the reduced Planck mass, which is ≈ 4.341 × 10 kg = 2.435 × 10 GeV/c. The added factor of 1/√(8π) simplifies a number of equations in general relativity. Quantum effects are typified by the magnitude of Planck's constant.

-- QUDT"""@en ;
    emmo:qudtReference "http://qudt.org/vocab/unit/PER-PlanckMass2"^^xsd:string ;
    emmo:unitSymbol "/mₚ²"^^xsd:string ;
    emmo:wikipediaReference "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Planck_units"^^xsd:string .

