emmo:PlanckTime a owl:NamedIndividual,
        emmo:EMMO_02e894c3_b793_4197_b120_3442e08f58d1,
        emmo:EMMO_15344998_4490_4b40_b242_c3d92e5cdc27,
        emmo:EMMO_868ae137_4d25_493e_b270_21ea3d94849e,
        emmo:EMMO_b081b346_7279_46ef_9a3d_2c088fcd79f4 ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy <https://w3id.org/emmo/disciplines/units/unclassifiedunits-abox#>,
        "http://qudt.org/2.1/vocab/unit"^^xsd:string ;
    skos:altLabel "Planck Time"@en ;
    skos:prefLabel "PlanckTime"@en ;
    emmo:EMMO_8189b42e_0995_423a_a26c_51168b27c3cf 5.39124e-44 ;
    emmo:EMMO_d088a3cb_d3e3_4eb2_9897_00aef0cb00cd 0e+00 ;
    emmo:elucidation """In physics, the Planck time, denoted by tₚ, is the unit of time in the system of natural units known as Planck units. It is the time required for light to travel, in a vacuum, a distance of 1 Planck length. The unit is named after Max Planck, who was the first to propose it. tₚ ≡ √(ℏ G/c⁵) ≈ 5.39106(32) × 10⁻⁴⁴ s where, c is the speed of light in a vacuum, ℏ is the reduced Planck's constant (defined as ℏ = h/(2 π)) and G is the gravitational constant. The two digits between parentheses denote the standard error of the estimated value.

-- QUDT"""@en ;
    emmo:qudtReference "http://qudt.org/vocab/unit/PlanckTime"^^xsd:string ;
    emmo:unitSymbol "tₚ"^^xsd:string ;
    emmo:wikipediaReference "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Planck_units"^^xsd:string .

