emmo:RelativePermeability a owl:NamedIndividual,
        emmo:EMMO_15344998_4490_4b40_b242_c3d92e5cdc27,
        emmo:EMMO_868ae137_4d25_493e_b270_21ea3d94849e,
        emmo:EMMO_b081b346_7279_46ef_9a3d_2c088fcd79f4,
        emmo:EMMO_c2f5ee66_579c_44c6_a2e9_fa2eaa9fa4da ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy <https://w3id.org/emmo/disciplines/units/unclassifiedunits-abox#>,
        "http://qudt.org/2.1/vocab/unit"^^xsd:string ;
    skos:altLabel "Relative Permeability"@en ;
    skos:prefLabel "RelativePermeability"@en ;
    emmo:EMMO_8189b42e_0995_423a_a26c_51168b27c3cf 1.256637e-06 ;
    emmo:EMMO_d088a3cb_d3e3_4eb2_9897_00aef0cb00cd 0e+00 ;
    emmo:elucidation """In multiphase flow in porous media, the relative permeability of a phase is a dimensionless measure of the effective permeability of that phase. It is the ratio of the effective permeability of that phase to the absolute permeability. It can be viewed as an adaptation of Darcy's law to multiphase flow. For two-phase flow in porous media given steady-state conditions, we can write where is the flux, is the pressure drop, is the viscosity.

-- QUDT"""@en ;
    emmo:qudtReference "http://qudt.org/vocab/unit/PERMEABILITY_REL"^^xsd:string ;
    emmo:unitSymbol "kᵣ"^^xsd:string ;
    emmo:wikipediaReference "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Relative_permeability"^^xsd:string .

emmo:RelativePermittivity a owl:NamedIndividual,
        emmo:EMMO_15344998_4490_4b40_b242_c3d92e5cdc27,
        emmo:EMMO_868ae137_4d25_493e_b270_21ea3d94849e,
        emmo:EMMO_b081b346_7279_46ef_9a3d_2c088fcd79f4,
        emmo:EMMO_c2f5ee66_579c_44c6_a2e9_fa2eaa9fa4da ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy <https://w3id.org/emmo/disciplines/units/unclassifiedunits-abox#>,
        "http://qudt.org/2.1/vocab/unit"^^xsd:string ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "http://www.ncert.nic.in/html/learning_basket/electricity/electricity/charges%20&%20fields/absolute_permittivity.htm"^^xsd:string ;
    skos:altLabel "Relative Permittivity"@en ;
    skos:prefLabel "RelativePermittivity"@en ;
    emmo:EMMO_8189b42e_0995_423a_a26c_51168b27c3cf 8.854188e-12 ;
    emmo:EMMO_d088a3cb_d3e3_4eb2_9897_00aef0cb00cd 0e+00 ;
    emmo:elucidation """The `relative permittivity` of a material under given conditions reflects the extent to which it concentrates electrostatic lines of flux. In technical terms, it is the ratio of the amount of electrical energy stored in a material by an applied voltage, relative to that stored in a vacuum. Likewise, it is also the ratio of the capacitance of a capacitor using that material as a dielectric, compared to a similar capacitor that has a vacuum as its dielectric. Relative permittivity is a dimensionless number that is in general complex. The imaginary portion of the permittivity corresponds to a phase shift of the polarization P relative to E and leads to the attenuation of electromagnetic waves passing through the medium.
ε_r(w) = (ε(w))/(ε_O) where ε_r(w) is the complex frequency-dependent absolute permittivity of the material, and ε_O is the vacuum permittivity.

-- QUDT"""@en ;
    emmo:qudtReference "http://qudt.org/vocab/unit/PERMITTIVITY_REL"^^xsd:string ;
    emmo:ucumCode "[eps_0]"^^xsd:string ;
    emmo:unitSymbol "εᵣ"^^xsd:string ;
    emmo:wikipediaReference "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Relative_static_permittivity?oldid=334224492"^^xsd:string .

emmo:Rem a owl:NamedIndividual,
        emmo:EMMO_8246541a_f1f6_4d03_8bd7_fc6b76d17375,
        emmo:EMMO_847f1d9f_205e_46c1_8cb6_a9e479421f88,
        emmo:EMMO_868ae137_4d25_493e_b270_21ea3d94849e,
        emmo:EMMO_b081b346_7279_46ef_9a3d_2c088fcd79f4 ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy <https://w3id.org/emmo/disciplines/units/unclassifiedunits-abox#>,
        "http://qudt.org/2.1/vocab/unit"^^xsd:string ;
    skos:prefLabel "Rem"@en ;
    emmo:EMMO_8189b42e_0995_423a_a26c_51168b27c3cf 1e-02 ;
    emmo:EMMO_d088a3cb_d3e3_4eb2_9897_00aef0cb00cd 0e+00 ;
    emmo:elucidation """A Rem is a deprecated unit used to measure the biological effects of ionizing radiation. The rem is defined as equal to 0.01 sievert, which is the more commonly used unit outside of the United States. Equivalent dose, effective dose, and committed dose can all be measured in units of rem. These quantities are products of the absorbed dose in rads and weighting factors. These factors must be selected for each exposure situation; there is no universally applicable conversion constant from rad to rem. A rem is a large dose of radiation, so the millirem (mrem), which is one thousandth of a rem, is often used for the dosages commonly encountered, such as the amount of radiation received from medical x-rays and background sources.

-- QUDT"""@en ;
    emmo:qudtReference "http://qudt.org/vocab/unit/REM"^^xsd:string ;
    emmo:ucumCode "REM"^^xsd:string ;
    emmo:unitSymbol "rem"^^xsd:string ;
    emmo:wikipediaReference "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roentgen_equivalent_man"^^xsd:string .

