emmo:Statvolt a owl:NamedIndividual,
        emmo:EMMO_2e7e5796_4a80_4d73_bb84_f31138446c0c,
        emmo:EMMO_8246541a_f1f6_4d03_8bd7_fc6b76d17375,
        emmo:EMMO_868ae137_4d25_493e_b270_21ea3d94849e,
        emmo:EMMO_b081b346_7279_46ef_9a3d_2c088fcd79f4 ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy <https://w3id.org/emmo/disciplines/units/unclassifiedunits-abox#>,
        "http://qudt.org/2.1/vocab/unit"^^xsd:string ;
    skos:prefLabel "Statvolt"@en ;
    emmo:EMMO_8189b42e_0995_423a_a26c_51168b27c3cf 2.997925e+02 ;
    emmo:EMMO_d088a3cb_d3e3_4eb2_9897_00aef0cb00cd 0e+00 ;
    emmo:elucidation """"statvolt" is a unit of voltage and electrical potential used in the cgs system of units. The conversion to the SI system is 1 statvolt = 299.792458 volts. The conversion factor 299.792458 is simply the numerical value of the speed of light in m/s divided by 106. The statvolt is also defined in the cgs system as 1 erg / esu. It is a useful unit for electromagnetism because one statvolt per centimetre is equal in magnitude to one gauss. Thus, for example, an electric field of one statvolt/cm has the same energy density as a magnetic field of one gauss. Likewise, a plane wave propagating in a vacuum has perpendicular electric and magnetic fields such that for every gauss of magnetic field intensity there is one statvolt/cm of electric field intensity. The abvolt is another option for a unit of voltage in the cgs system.

-- QUDT"""@en ;
    emmo:qudtReference "http://qudt.org/vocab/unit/V_Stat"^^xsd:string ;
    emmo:unitSymbol "statV"^^xsd:string ;
    emmo:wikipediaReference "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statvolt?oldid=491769750"^^xsd:string .

emmo:StatvoltPerCentiMetre a owl:NamedIndividual,
        emmo:EMMO_8246541a_f1f6_4d03_8bd7_fc6b76d17375,
        emmo:EMMO_b081b346_7279_46ef_9a3d_2c088fcd79f4,
        emmo:EMMO_c6d4a5e0_7e95_44df_a6db_84ee0a8bbc8e,
        emmo:EMMO_ebf9a5c6_ca80_45d4_a991_24a1bf4b6720 ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy <https://w3id.org/emmo/disciplines/units/unclassifiedunits-abox#>,
        "http://qudt.org/2.1/vocab/unit"^^xsd:string ;
    skos:altLabel "Statvolt per Centimetre"@en ;
    skos:prefLabel "StatvoltPerCentiMetre"^^xsd:string ;
    emmo:EMMO_8189b42e_0995_423a_a26c_51168b27c3cf 2.997925e+04 ;
    emmo:EMMO_d088a3cb_d3e3_4eb2_9897_00aef0cb00cd 0e+00 ;
    emmo:elucidation """One statvolt per centimetre is equal in magnitude to one gauss. For example, an electric field of one statvolt/cm has the same energy density as a magnetic field of one gauss. Likewise, a plane wave propagating in a vacuum has perpendicular electric and magnetic fields such that for every gauss of magnetic field intensity there is one statvolt/cm of electric field intensity.
The abvolt is another option for a unit of voltage in the cgs system.

-- QUDT"""@en ;
    emmo:qudtReference "http://qudt.org/vocab/unit/V_Stat-PER-CentiM"^^xsd:string ;
    emmo:unitSymbol "statV/cm"^^xsd:string ;
    emmo:wikipediaReference "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statvolt"^^xsd:string .

emmo:Stere a owl:NamedIndividual,
        emmo:EMMO_8246541a_f1f6_4d03_8bd7_fc6b76d17375,
        emmo:EMMO_868ae137_4d25_493e_b270_21ea3d94849e,
        emmo:EMMO_9141801c_c539_4c72_b423_8c74ff6b8f05,
        emmo:EMMO_b081b346_7279_46ef_9a3d_2c088fcd79f4 ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy <https://w3id.org/emmo/disciplines/units/unclassifiedunits-abox#>,
        "http://qudt.org/2.1/vocab/unit"^^xsd:string ;
    skos:prefLabel "Stere"@en ;
    emmo:EMMO_8189b42e_0995_423a_a26c_51168b27c3cf 1e+00 ;
    emmo:EMMO_d088a3cb_d3e3_4eb2_9897_00aef0cb00cd 0e+00 ;
    emmo:elucidation """The stere is a unit of volume in the original metric system equal to one cubic metre.  The stere is typically used for measuring large quantities of firewood or other cut wood, while the cubic meter is used for uncut wood. It is not part of the modern metric system (SI). In Dutch there's also a kuub, short for kubieke meter which is similar but different.

-- QUDT"""@en ;
    emmo:qudtReference "http://qudt.org/vocab/unit/STR"^^xsd:string ;
    emmo:ucumCode "st"^^xsd:string ;
    emmo:unitSymbol "st"^^xsd:string ;
    emmo:wikipediaReference "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stère?oldid=393570287"^^xsd:string .

emmo:Stilb a owl:NamedIndividual,
        emmo:EMMO_4000d06d_8594_4263_ba72_5d9440b66c5e,
        emmo:EMMO_8246541a_f1f6_4d03_8bd7_fc6b76d17375,
        emmo:EMMO_868ae137_4d25_493e_b270_21ea3d94849e,
        emmo:EMMO_b081b346_7279_46ef_9a3d_2c088fcd79f4 ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy <https://w3id.org/emmo/disciplines/units/unclassifiedunits-abox#>,
        "http://qudt.org/2.1/vocab/unit"^^xsd:string ;
    skos:prefLabel "Stilb"@en ;
    emmo:EMMO_8189b42e_0995_423a_a26c_51168b27c3cf 1e+04 ;
    emmo:EMMO_d088a3cb_d3e3_4eb2_9897_00aef0cb00cd 0e+00 ;
    emmo:elucidation """The `stilb (sb)` is the CGS unit of luminance for objects that are not self-luminous. It is equal to one candela per square centimeter or 10 nits (candelas per square meter). The name was coined by the French physicist A. Blondel around 1920. It comes from the Greek word stilbein meaning 'to glitter'. It was in common use in Europe up to World War I. In North America self-explanatory terms such as candle per square inch and candle per square meter were more common. The unit has since largely been replaced by the SI unit: candela per square meter.

-- QUDT"""@en ;
    emmo:qudtReference "http://qudt.org/vocab/unit/STILB"^^xsd:string ;
    emmo:ucumCode "sb"^^xsd:string ;
    emmo:unitSymbol "sb"^^xsd:string ;
    emmo:wikipediaReference "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stilb?oldid=375748497"^^xsd:string .

